<br>
1. Page by page breakdowns, describing each character's actions, dress, and placement as well as background and props for that setting.<br>
<br>
2. Reviewing the dialog so the characters sound their ages.  The two primary characters are 8 and 12 year old girls, so I'm trying to make sure they don't sound like adults, and one sounds younger and more innocent than the other.<br>
<br>
3. Trying to avoid the characters <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> simply state</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> what's happening, and instead sound like they're actually <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> living through</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> those events.  One of the girls' parents are divorcing.  That's <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> simply stating</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> the event.  A friend of mine once said about his parent's divorce, &quot;They're putting different colored sticky-notes on everything.  I never know what color note I am.&quot;  To me, that sounds like he's [/i]living[/i] through it.<br>
<br>
4. Ensuring events and people are foreshadowed.  James Patterson's mysteries frequently have villians show up <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> presto!</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> seemingly out of the blue at the end of the book, without any clues leading in that direction.  I dislike that, and am trying to avoid it.  <br>
<br>
